    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-29T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-29T03:00:00-05:00" n="319"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d319">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5018/46: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-29T15:00:00+07:00"
                            >December 29, 1943—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 11, 1944—4 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–110. Embassy’s telegram no. 2039, October 29, 2 p.m.<note n="14"
                        xml:id="d319fn14">Not printed.</note> Following is substance of telegram
                    dated December 24 from Drumright at Loyang: <pb facs="0406" n="396"
                        xml:id="pg_396"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Famine conditions in Honan remain approximately as described in my
                            telegram of October 27. There is widespread privation but little actual
                            starvation at present. The most difficult period, however, will be from
                            March until the wheat is harvested in late May. The majority of the
                            refugees come from the flooded region in vicinity of Chengchow and from
                            the area north of the Yellow River where the shortage of food is acute
                            and prices are higher. The authorities are apparently doing little
                            relief work at present; foreign relief organizations are doing excellent
                            work but their efforts are limited by scarcity of funds. After trip
                            through Honan it seems clear that the burden of taxation, various
                            official exactions and transportation difficulties have figured largely
                            in the impoverishment of the people of this province.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
